comment: Look your survey is not concern with breath, where as breath is an integral part of no mind situation. A normal person takes about 16 respiration (1 inhalation+ 1 exhalation). Same may become "Zero" during meditation or during the flow activity, whereas same will exceed 30 during sexited and excited state. Besides this, breath has 2 characteristics namely - frequency  and quality. The quality varies from silent to very coarse, which becomes loud during anger and other excited states. I personally feel any study on mental silence must have questions to frequency and quality of breath.

comment: It's a really interesting thing, this "mental silence". I had never heard of it before and am interested in learning more about it--namely what happens to the brain to cause that, what happens during that state, and what it "feels like". I am confused as to whether there is an amnesia effect (that wasn't really made clear) or if it is more like, for example, when I take my adderall sometimes I will tell someone I will leave the house in 10 minutes, and then next thing I know, 3 hours have passed. I wonder if it's like that because there is still thought going on when I lose track of time in such a fashion--it's just that the thought is concentrated only on whatever thing I am doing at the time. It seems inconceivable that someone could be completely void of any thought whatsoever. And if it is indeed possible, why in the world would someone want that? I do not understand that part. I want as much time possible on this earth; why would I deliberately go unconscious? If one is depressed or something and wishes to escape, can't they just try to go to sleep or distract themselves with a book or something? (Sorry, just thinking aloud because it is indeed an interesting concept to me.)

comment: The Mental Silence for which so many questions are being asked is NOT the objective of meditation.  The objective of meditation is to search for truth of the self. This self knowledge frees the mind of egoic, destructive patterns of thought and emotions leading to a silence.   Any activity of the mind, which has a goal is not meditation. It can be concentration.  Silence cannot be made as a goal to be achieved in the future. If one does it, one gets trapped in time. Thought is deceptive and creates  silence. Silence as an objective of thought and created by thought is of no value, as it is false. A mind which is distorted, disturbed, fragmented - can try many activities in the name of meditation but it will lead to more distortion. Even its Silence is distorted.

m.training.desc: Dynamic Meditation, Kundalini Meditation, Watching your breath technique, Yoga
m.desc: when i am ready for being in meditation, ie physically and mentally, i just watch me breathing, it then slows down and i can feel it traversing every part of my body. i then sense 'life' in those parts, in the entire body, i feel a certain frequency of vibration in the entire body, sometimes it is the heartbeats, sometimes something else. it is then i stop even observing and just be in this body of vibrations and life, and then even the sense of body boundary ceases and it feels that i am in an ocean of the vibrations and life force. it is then that i completely become part of the vibration and any sense of me ceases. during this practice i don't have any sense of time or space. it is at some point that i come out of this universal feeling. which i dont actually remember about the passage of time, but there sure is some change in the time shown by the clock
comment: it is a very interesting survey, though at times i am at loss of words, like for example, the question regarding the religion that i practice. i am unsure that i can explain my answer, it is like, i was a theist by birth, but after some self realizations, it felt forced, so i chose to find my own, and i went from being atheist to agnostic and then finally to theism, but this theism is not of a institutional religion, but it is more like, i am religiously following my own self, and self analysis. it is on the lines of taoism and buddhism but not even them. this happened when i first experienced complete mental silence during meditation. so it was hard to actually explain briefly.  and most of the answers were not instantaneous but taking into account of my past and this year's experiences together, more like a statistical average answer.

The experience can be vribale, it can be difficult to be mentaly silent for more than a second or two but usually menta silence occurs spontaneously and on some occasions has lasted uninterrupted for some length of time. It is accompanied by vibratory awareness and a deep feeing of joy, bliss and peace.

Unfortunately, there is sometime limited time for meditation as I have to stop and go to work etc. But when no such pressure apply, meditation is a partcularly timeless activity. When engaged in problem solving, work, physical activity etc.time often passes quickly so I have tried to indicate that in my responses.

m.desc: I practice silent meditation several times a week, usually listening to a guided meditation or as less structured relaxation activity at work or before falling asleep.  I typically start by following my breath but then usually switch to listening to the sounds around me.  "Mental silence" is hard to attain and fleeting, but I typically "touch" it a few times in a session, albeit briefly.  I would describe it as a period where I suddenly feel balanced, still, and completely content with the present.
comment: The question about "what percentage of the time are you successful in becoming mentally silent" was difficult to answer because I don't know how you are defining success.  I would say that in a 30 minute meditation, my mind is only truly silent for a short period, less than 10% of the session.  But I probably experience that in 75-80% of my sessions.  So I'm not sure if you'd say I'm successful 80% of the time, or 10%!

comment: I think there's a difference in the kind of thoughtless awareness you get when meditating and the kind of mental silences that occur in problems like thought block, what can take place in really severe depression, and then of course in those spontaneous moments of mental silence that happen day to day. I'm not sure how you define thoughtless awareness, but meditation certainly doesn't do this, unless you restrict thoughts to words and images. It increases brain activity in the orbito-frontal cortex, the anterior insula, and the anterior cingulate cortex, to name only a few of the regions. I think that it spins a false narrative to suggest that true mental silence occurs from the practice of meditation, spiritual exercises, or doing things to cultivate the unconditioned mind. Under your definition it strikes me that mental silence occurs more purely in experiences of thought block. I think it's more appropriate to say that meditation alters your subjective state, but it doesn't reduce thought content, it just changes the kind of content you get. Because to truly get rid of that content altogether, that's a problem, not an ideal.

comment: Some of the survey questions seem to be "leading" the respondent and seem to have presumed preferential answers (or it seemed that way to me, anyway.) Some I didn't understand what on earth you meant, in which case, I left them blank, or if they were simply not applicable, I left them blank.  I was going to perhaps invite non-Rama students to take your survey, but I realized once I was taking it that they just wouldn't "get it".  BTW - What do you mean by day dreaming?  Day dreaming is thought, (so I thought) so how can you have complete silence of no thought in a deeply engrossed thought state? LOL  I don't know.  You obviously have studied something I'm not aware because that series of questions didn't make sense.  I appreciate your efforts; not quite sure what it's going to prove or if it even needs to prove anything.  My own personal experience is that Silence harmonizes everything and once familiar with it, if it becomes ones preference, it becomes almost effortless.  But my mentor (a Rama student like yourself) could go into complete silence at will and problem solve brilliantly!  So, yes, there is something to this quieting of the mind and EVERYONE can benefit.   Also, re: is it possible for everyone?  My answer "why not".  I was told by my mentor that Rama had said over a certain age it's almost impossible to change.  My experience, however through what Life taught me from the get-go.... the wiring I was born with,  through Christian Science, intuition, experiences pre-Rama, the gracious gift of being mentored by a Rama student and the gracious gift of afterward meeting Gangaji and Eli (my first experiences of COMPLETE STILLNESS with G & E... I had a 3-month honeymoon period where I operated out of complete stillness in daily life almost 24/7... the still moments far out-weighed the mental yapping and the thoughts were only those that were fluidly in response to the moment.)  Anyway in more recent times life threw me a curve ball; connected me with a 50-something year old being who was categorized as a drug addict, a felon, and had the emotional maturity of a 14 year old. I knew that wasn't who he really was on the inside. It's a both a long story and a short story, but the long and the short of it is.... he didn't know stillness and now he does.... he has composure... compassion.... he has beat his former perceived addiction... he is balanced... sensitive... aware.... and helps others.... and is constantly requested to help groups in hospitals and in parole programs. He got some hand-me-down kick-ass Rama-style compassion from me and got to go on a silent retreat with Gangaji and then Life unfolded an Enlightened doctor.  What a wonderful life.  He is what Gangaji and Eli's teacher would call "a candle that lights candle that lights another candle"...  and yes he read Surfing the Himalaya. and Surfing to Nirvana books and a bit of simple karma lessons life certain actions create certain responses (you know... practical stuff! LOL).  It's really wonderful...I mean really wonderful and this is the power of "the Light" or "Love" or "Truth" or "Silence" or the "Self" or whatever you choose to call It.  I can testify from real life experience that beautiful things can happen when we trust the Stillness to inform us.  But thoughts can be pretty cool especially when they are the inspired ones in a moment of non-quite noticing or from out of the blue in a moment of Silence - either one.  I have no opinion on any of this.  I just know what is. And I know Love. And I know for me I am profoundly, inexplicably, for no good reason "happy" and at the very least peaceful, regardless of circumstance when I rest in this Big quiet.  Thanks!   Cheers!

comment: Some questions regarding boredom are a little ambiguous. It may be necessary to ask if boredom motivates a person to engage in an activiy ie exercise, flow activity, daydreaming and to what extent these activities alleviate boredom as opposed to mental silence.  Also I think you should include questions such as what practices in meditation assist people to achieve mental silence.  This would be an interesting study to do. I am currently back at uni doing my Bachelor of Education Primary and am studying Meditation in Eatsern Religions as an elective. There is a lot of focus on Buddhist meditation and the techniques that meditators use to produce mental calm and focus the attention in the moment. When I think about my meditation I tend to use the affirmations and mantras of Sahaja Yoga to focus my attention when it wanders. I also focus on controlling my breath and using Shri mataji's photo as the "object" of my meditation, (a pratice not dissimilar to that used in Buddhist and Yogic meditation trances, when I compare the Sahaja yoga to meditation in Therevada Buddhism and Raja Yoga in Patanjali's eight limbs of yoga).

If some images start appearing in our head, we are told to try and focus our attention and sight to our brain, or the mid part of our stomach where our 'soul' is supposed to be.
